{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":1,"author":{"id":"128c1d13ad4755f2883987743b5984f0d6c0552d"},"timestamp":1564924741,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWU0NzY1NTI3NzU=","github-url":"https://github.com/ajayyy/SponsorBlockServer/issues/16","origin":"github"},"title":".","message":"There are only 2^32 IPv4 addresses, so in order to decrypt one IP address in the database (hashed 5000 times), you would need to calculate a maximum of 2^32 * 5000 SHA256 hashes.\n\n[An Nvidia GTX 1080 can apparently calculate 2829.7 * 10^6 of those per second](https://gist.github.com/epixoip/6ee29d5d626bd8dfe671a2d8f188b77b):  \n(2^32 * 5000) / (2829.7 * 10^6) = 7589 seconds = 2.1 hours\n\n[An AntMiner S9 can even do 14 * 10^12 double SHA256 hashes per second](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Mining_hardware_comparison):  \n(2^32 * 5000) / (14 * 10^12 * 2) = 0.77 seconds\n\nAlso, with the salt being global, you can essentially decrypt not only one, but all IP addresses in the database in that time.","files":null}]}